 @EnableWebSecurity:
  It is a marker annotation that tells Spring to activate the Spring Security framework and apply it to your web application.
  While modern Spring Boot (2.7+ and 3.x) has made this annotation optional in many cases,
  it remains the "on switch" for customizing how your application handles authentication and authorization.

1. What does it actually do?
    When you add @EnableWebSecurity to a configuration class, it performs several behind-the-scenes tasks:
      Registers the Filter Chain: It sets up the springSecurityFilterChain, 
              which is a stack of filters that intercept every incoming request to check for credentials, CSRF tokens, and session cookies.
      Enables Spring MVC Integration: It allows Spring Security to "talk" to your Spring MVC controllers,
              enabling things like @AuthenticationPrincipal to inject the current user into your methods.
      Activates Default Security: If you don't provide your own configuration, 
              it applies the default "Form Login" and "HTTP Basic" security to all endpoints.

2. Modern Implementation (Spring Boot 3.x / Security 6.x)
    In older versions, you had to extend WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter.That is now deprecated. 
    Today, you use @EnableWebSecurity along with a @Bean of type SecurityFilterChain to define your security rules.
        @Configuration
        @EnableWebSecurity
        public class SecurityConfig {
            @Bean
            public SecurityFilterChain securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
                http
                    .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
                        .requestMatchers("/public/**").permitAll() // No login needed
                        .anyRequest().authenticated()             // Everything else needs login
                    )
                    .formLogin(Customizer.withDefaults())         // Enable default login page
                    .httpBasic(Customizer.withDefaults());        // Enable basic auth for APIs
        
                return http.build();
            }
        }
3. Do I always need to type it?
      If you are using Spring Boot and have the spring-boot-starter-security dependency in your pom.xml,
      Spring Boot automatically detects this and acts as if @EnableWebSecurity is present.
      However, you should still use it explicitly when:
            You want to be explicit about where your security configuration lives.
            You are using a standard Spring MVC application (without Boot).
            You are creating highly customized security setups that might override Boot's auto-configuration.

4. Related Annotations
    Often, you’ll see @EnableWebSecurity paired with these:
    @Configuration: Required so Spring knows this class contains @Bean definitions.
    @EnableMethodSecurity: Use this if you want to protect specific methods using annotations like @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')").


The Big Picture — Spring Security Architecture:
      [Client]
            |
            | HTTP Request
            v
        [DelegatingFilterProxy]           <-- Servlet world to Spring bridge
            |
            v
        [FilterChainProxy]                <-- holds all SecurityFilterChain(s)
            |
            v
        [SecurityFilterChain]             <-- your configured chain
            |
            |-- [SecurityContextPersistenceFilter]
            |-- [UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter]
            |-- [BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter]
            |-- [ExceptionTranslationFilter]
            |-- [AuthorizationFilter]
            |
            v
        [Your Controller / Service]

Every HTTP request enters the Servlet container,
        hits DelegatingFilterProxy (which bridges the Servlet world to Spring's bean context), 
        is handed to FilterChainProxy, which picks the matching SecurityFilterChain and runs each filter in order. 
Authentication happens in the middle of that chain — 
      the result is stored in SecurityContextHolder as a ThreadLocal, 
      and by the time your controller runs, 
      Authentication is simply there waiting.

The Filter Chain Flow — Step by Step:

        Incoming Request: GET /api/orders
        Header: Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGci...
            |
            v
        [1. SecurityContextPersistenceFilter]
            |   Loads SecurityContext (stateless = empty each time)
            |
            v
        [2. BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter]
            |   Extracts token from Authorization header
            |
            v
        [3. AuthenticationManager.authenticate()]
            |   Wraps token in BearerTokenAuthenticationToken
            |   Delegates to AuthenticationProvider
            |
            v
        [4. JwtAuthenticationProvider]
            |   JwtDecoder verifies:
            |     - Signature (RSA public key / JWKS)
            |     - Expiry (exp claim)
            |     - Issuer (iss claim)
            |     - Audience (aud claim)
            |
            |---[VALID?]
            |       |
            |      YES                          NO
            |       |                            |
            v       v                            v
        [5a. Store in SecurityContextHolder]  [5b. ExceptionTranslationFilter]
            |   JwtAuthenticationToken              |   AuthenticationEntryPoint
            |   (principal + authorities)           |   Returns HTTP 401
            v
        [6. AuthorizationFilter]
            |   Checks roles / scopes
            |   @PreAuthorize / HttpSecurity rules
            |
            |---[AUTHORIZED?]
                    |
                   YES                          NO
                    |                            |
                    v                            v
            [Controller executes]          HTTP 403 Forbidden

