    Spring Boot auto-configures a default SecurityFilterChain, a UserDetailsService with a random password, and basic form login. 
    You override all of it with your own @Bean.
    The SecurityFilterChain — your primary config
          @Configuration
          @EnableWebSecurity
          @EnableMethodSecurity          // enables @PreAuthorize, @PostAuthorize, @Secured
          public class SecurityConfig {
              @Bean
              public SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
                  http
                      .csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable())               // stateless APIs don't need CSRF
                      .sessionManagement(sm -> sm
                          .sessionCreationPolicy(SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS))
                      .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
                          .requestMatchers("/api/auth/**").permitAll()
                          .requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
                          .requestMatchers(HttpMethod.GET, "/api/products/**").hasAnyRole("USER","ADMIN")
                          .anyRequest().authenticated()
                      )
                      .oauth2ResourceServer(oauth2 -> oauth2
                          .jwt(jwt -> jwt.decoder(jwtDecoder()))  // JWT validation configured here
                      );
                  return http.build();
              }
          }
AuthenticationManager and AuthenticationProvider — are they needed?
This is a key question. The short answer: for JWT resource servers, no — Spring Boot wires them automatically. For custom login flows, yes.

  Scenario                          AuthManager?   AuthProvider?
  --------------------------------  -------------  ----------------
  JWT Resource Server (validate     NO             NO
  incoming tokens only)             (auto-wired)   (auto-wired)

  Login endpoint (credentials       YES            YES
  exchanged for token)              (expose @Bean) (DaoAuth...)

  Custom token type (API key,       YES            YES
  TOTP, certificate-based)          (expose @Bean) (write custom)

  OAuth2 Authorization Server       YES            Managed by
  (issuing tokens)                                 spring-auth-server

  Rule of thumb:
    - Receiving & validating tokens  --> JwtDecoder only
    - Issuing tokens from credentials --> need the full manager chain

      For a pure JWT resource server (which most microservices are — they receive tokens they didn't issue),
      the complete minimum config is just the SecurityFilterChain above plus a JwtDecoder:
          @Bean
          public JwtDecoder jwtDecoder() {
              // Option A — validate against a public key (most common)
              return NimbusJwtDecoder.withPublicKey(rsaPublicKey()).build();
              // Option B — validate against JWKS endpoint (OAuth2 provider like Keycloak)
              // return NimbusJwtDecoder.withJwkSetUri("https://auth-server/.well-known/jwks.json").build();
          }
      For a login endpoint (where users exchange credentials for a token), you DO need the manager:
           @Bean
            public AuthenticationManager authManager(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
                AuthenticationManagerBuilder builder =
                    http.getSharedObject(AuthenticationManagerBuilder.class);
                builder.userDetailsService(userDetailsService())
                       .passwordEncoder(passwordEncoder());
                return builder.build();
            }
              @Bean
              public UserDetailsService userDetailsService() {
                  return username -> userRepository.findByUsername(username)
                      .map(u -> User.withUsername(u.getUsername())
                                    .password(u.getPasswordHash())
                                    .roles(u.getRoles().toArray(String[]::new))
                                    .build())
                      .orElseThrow(() -> new UsernameNotFoundException("User not found: " + username));
              }
              
              @Bean
              public PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder() {
                  return new BCryptPasswordEncoder();
              }
      Your login controller then calls the manager directly:
          @RestController
          @RequestMapping("/api/auth")
          public class AuthController {
              private final AuthenticationManager authManager;
              private final JwtTokenService tokenService;
              @PostMapping("/login")
              public ResponseEntity<TokenResponse> login(@RequestBody LoginRequest req) {
                  Authentication auth = authManager.authenticate(
                      new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(req.username(), req.password())
                  );
                  // auth is now populated with UserDetails + granted authorities
                  String token = tokenService.generateToken(auth);
                  return ResponseEntity.ok(new TokenResponse(token));
              }
          }
Token Generation — Server-Level Certificate (mTLS & RS256)
    Yes, you can and should generate JWTs signed with a server-level RSA or EC private key (asymmetric signing).
    This is far more secure than a shared secret (HS256) because services only need the public key to verify — they never hold the private key.
Generating a JWT with RSA (RS256) — using the server's private key
      @Service
      public class JwtTokenService {
      
          private final RSAPrivateKey privateKey;   // loaded from server keystore / cert
          private final RSAPublicKey  publicKey;
      
          @Value("${app.jwt.expiry-minutes:60}")
          private long expiryMinutes;
      
          public String generateToken(Authentication auth) {
              Instant now     = Instant.now();
              Instant expires = now.plusSeconds(expiryMinutes * 60);
      
              UserDetails user = (UserDetails) auth.getPrincipal();
              List<String> roles = auth.getAuthorities().stream()
                  .map(GrantedAuthority::getAuthority)
                  .toList();
      
              return JWT.create()
                  .withIssuer("https://my-service.example.com")
                  .withSubject(user.getUsername())
                  .withIssuedAt(Date.from(now))
                  .withExpiresAt(Date.from(expires))
                  .withClaim("roles", roles)
                  .withClaim("jti", UUID.randomUUID().toString())  // unique token ID for revocation
                  .sign(Algorithm.RSA256(publicKey, privateKey));  // signed with private key
          }
      }
Loading the key from a PKCS12 keystore (the server certificate)
        @Configuration
        public class KeyConfig {
        
            @Value("${app.jwt.keystore-path}")
            private String keystorePath;
        
            @Value("${app.jwt.keystore-password}")
            private String keystorePassword;
        
            @Value("${app.jwt.key-alias}")
            private String keyAlias;
        
            @Bean
            public RSAPrivateKey jwtPrivateKey() throws Exception {
                KeyStore ks = KeyStore.getInstance("PKCS12");
                try (InputStream is = new ClassPathResource(keystorePath).getInputStream()) {
                    ks.load(is, keystorePassword.toCharArray());
                }
                return (RSAPrivateKey) ks.getKey(keyAlias, keystorePassword.toCharArray());
            }
        
            @Bean
            public RSAPublicKey jwtPublicKey() throws Exception {
                KeyStore ks = KeyStore.getInstance("PKCS12");
                try (InputStream is = new ClassPathResource(keystorePath).getInputStream()) {
                    ks.load(is, keystorePassword.toCharArray());
                }
                Certificate cert = ks.getCertificate(keyAlias);
                return (RSAPublicKey) cert.getPublicKey();
            }
        }
The resource server (same or different service) validates with only the public key —
      the private key never leaves the issuer service. For inter-service trust, you publish the public key as a JWKS endpoint:
      @RestController
      public class JwksController {
      
          @Autowired RSAPublicKey publicKey;
      
          @GetMapping("/.well-known/jwks.json")
          public Map<String, Object> jwks() {
              RSAKey jwk = new RSAKey.Builder(publicKey)
                  .keyUse(KeyUse.SIGNATURE)
                  .algorithm(JWSAlgorithm.RS256)
                  .keyID("my-key-id")
                  .build();
              return new JWKSet(jwk).toJSONObject();
          }
      }
mTLS — certificate-based authentication at the TLS layer
    mTLS (mutual TLS) goes a step further — the client presents its own X.509 certificate during the TLS handshake. 
    Spring Security can extract the client cert and authenticate from it directly, with no JWT needed:
      http
          .x509(x509 -> x509
              .subjectPrincipalRegex("CN=(.*?)(?:,|$)")  // extract username from cert CN
              .userDetailsService(userDetailsService())
          );
      The server's application.properties must request client certs:
      propertiesserver.ssl.client-auth=need
      server.ssl.key-store=classpath:server.p12
      server.ssl.key-store-password=changeit
      server.ssl.trust-store=classpath:truststore.p12
      server.ssl.trust-store-password=changeit
    This is common in service-to-service auth inside a zero-trust network — 
        each service has a cert issued by an internal CA, and no bearer tokens are needed at all.

API Gateway Integration:
The gateway sits in front of all services. There are two valid patterns.

 PATTERN A — GATEWAY VALIDATES TOKEN
  ------------------------------------

  [Client]
      | Bearer token
      v
  [API Gateway]
      |   JwtDecoder validates signature + claims
      |   Extracts user info
      |   TokenRelay filter strips outer token
      |   Adds internal headers: X-User-Id, X-Roles
      |
      v
  [Order Service]  [User Service]  [Product Service]
      |   Trusts internal headers (no spring-security needed)
      |   Only reachable from gateway network (firewall rules)

  Pros: single validation point, simpler services
  Cons: gateway bypass = no security, single point of failure


  PATTERN B — GATEWAY FORWARDS, EACH SERVICE VALIDATES
  -----------------------------------------------------

  [Client]
      | Bearer token
      v
  [API Gateway]
      |   Rate limiting, routing only
      |   TokenRelay filter forwards Authorization header unchanged
      |
      v
  [Order Service]  [User Service]  [Product Service]
      |   Each has its own SecurityFilterChain
      |   Each runs BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter
      |   Each validates JWT against JWKS endpoint

  Pros: defense in depth, zero-trust, services are independent
  Cons: repeated validation overhead, each service needs security config



